  "prompt": "Are there legal frameworks in place to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are robust and comprehensive legal frameworks in place in most countries around the world to combat money laundering (AML). These frameworks are typically built upon international standards and guidelines, and are adapted to suit each country's specific legal system and risk profile.\n\nHere's a breakdown of the key elements and international influences:\n\n**International Standards and Organizations:**\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF is the global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist financing (AML/CFT). It develops the \"FATF Recommendations\" (also known as the \"40 Recommendations\"), which are recognized as the international standard for AML/CFT measures. These recommendations cover a wide range of topics, including:\n    *   Criminalization of money laundering and terrorist financing\n    *   Customer due diligence (CDD) requirements for financial institutions and other designated non-financial businesses and professions (DNFBPs)\n    *   Record-keeping and reporting obligations\n    ",
